# 🎤 Demo Script — Intelligent Adaptive Mock Platform
**Presenter:** Intern  
**Audience:** Engineering Manager  
**Duration:** ~15–20 minutes  
**Format:** Live demo with talking points

---

## 🟢 OPENING — Set the Stage (2 min)

> *Open the landing page. Let it load visibly.*

**Say:**
> "So the problem I set out to solve is something every dev team hits at some point — you're building a frontend or a microservice, but the backend you depend on isn't ready, or it's flaky, or it's in production and you can't hit it during testing. The typical fix is to write a mock server by hand — hardcode some JSON, maybe write a few if-else conditions. But those go stale the moment the real API changes, and nobody notices until something breaks in prod.
>
> This platform makes that whole problem go away. It's called the **Intelligent Adaptive Mock Platform**. The key word is *adaptive* — instead of you writing the mock, the platform watches real traffic and learns it automatically. Let me show you how."

---

## 🔵 PHASE 1 — Proxy Mode & Learning Engine (4 min)

> *Log in. Navigate to the Control Deck (dashboard).*

### 1a. The Two Modes

**Say:**
> "The platform has two operating modes — you can see the toggle here.
>
> - **Proxy Mode** is where you start. Every request goes through the platform and gets forwarded to the real backend. But while it does that — silently, in the background — the platform is *studying* every request and response.
> - **Mock Mode** is where you switch to later. The real backend is offline, but the platform has already learned how it behaves, so it replays that behavior from memory.
>
> You point your app or Postman at this server instead of your real API. That's all the integration needed."

### 1b. Point out the Learning Toggle and Target URL

**Say:**
> "There's a learning toggle here. When it's on, every proxied request is buffered and processed every 5 seconds by the learning engine. I can also set the target URL — the real backend — right from this panel. No config file changes, no restarts."

### 1c. Explain what it learns

**Say:**
> "What exactly does it learn? For every endpoint it discovers — uniquely identified by HTTP method and path — it builds up a statistical model:
> - The **average latency** and its variance
> - The **error rate** and which status codes come back
> - The **full JSON schema** of the request and response — not just the keys, but the data types, the nesting, which fields are nullable
>
> This all happens automatically. There's no YAML to write, no OpenAPI spec to maintain."

---

## 🟡 PHASE 2 — Explorer Page (3 min)

> *Navigate to `/admin/explorer`.*

**Say:**
> "Once traffic flows in, I can see everything the platform has learned on the Explorer page. This shows all discovered endpoints with pagination and live search. Let me click into one.
>
> You can see — the platform has inferred the average response time, the error rate, the status code distribution, and a full preview of the request and response schema. It normalizes path parameters automatically — so `/users/123` and `/users/456` are both recognized as `/users/{id}`, not treated as two separate endpoints."

> *Scroll down to show drift alerts if any are present.*

**Say:**
> "And this red badge here — that's a Contract Drift alert. I'll explain that in a moment. Let's first switch to Mock Mode and see the AI in action."

---

## 🔴 PHASE 3 — Mock Mode & AI Generation (3 min)

> *Switch platform to Mock Mode from the dashboard.*

**Say:**
> "I've just switched to Mock Mode. The platform is now completely standalone — the real backend is no longer needed. Let me fire a request at the same endpoint we just saw."

> *Open a terminal or use a pre-pasted curl command. Example:*
```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:8000/api/analyze \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"student_id": "s_999", "topic": "recursion"}'
```

**Say:**
> "And we get back a realistic, structured response — same shape, same keys, same data types as the real API. But notice the values are *fresh* — they're not a recording, they're a GPT-4o-generated variation.
>
> Here's how that works: the platform extracts a golden example from what it learned, feeds it to GPT-4o-mini as a few-shot example along with the incoming request, and instructs the model to produce a realistic variation. Things like scores change by ±10-30%, descriptions are rewritten, arrays have different items.
>
> The result feels like a real response — not a stub. And because it's context-aware, if I send a different student ID or a different topic, the response will be different. It understands semantics, not just structure."

**Say:**
> "There's also a fallback chain — if OpenAI isn't available, it falls back to pure schema-tree reconstruction. And if no schema has been learned yet, it returns a safe placeholder. The mock never crashes."

---

## 🟣 PHASE 4 — Contract Drift Detection (3 min)

> *Navigate to Drift Alerts from the dashboard.*

**Say:**
> "Now here's one of my favourite features — Contract Drift Detection.
>
> In real teams, APIs change. A field gets renamed, a status code changes, a new field appears. If your mock doesn't know about this, it silently diverges from reality — and you only find out when QA or prod breaks.
>
> This platform detects that automatically. Every response that comes through in Proxy Mode is compared against the learned schema. If something has changed — say a field that was always a string is now a number, or a new required field appeared — it raises a Drift Alert with a severity score and a human-readable narration."

> *Point to a drift alert's narration field.*

**Say:**
> "This plain-English summary is generated right here in the backend — no AI call needed. It describes exactly what changed and in which field. The on-call dev or the QA engineer can look at this and immediately understand what broke and when."

**Say:**
> "Alerts can be resolved once the mock is updated. There's no noise — only unresolved drifts are surfaced."

---

## 🟠 PHASE 5 — Health Monitor (2 min)

> *Navigate to the Health section.*

**Say:**
> "The platform also watches for performance anomalies. For every endpoint, it maintains a rolling baseline of latency, error rate, and response size. If a new request comes in and the latency spikes by more than a threshold — determined per-endpoint because different APIs have different normal ranges — it flags it as a latency anomaly.
>
> Same for error spikes and payload size changes. Each observation gets a health score from 0 to 100. This is how you catch a backend that's degrading before your users notice."

—

## 🟤 PHASE 6 — OpenAPI Export (1 min)

> *Navigate to `/admin/docs` or the Swagger page.*

**Say:**
> "One last thing — the platform can export everything it has learned as a valid OpenAPI 3.0 specification. This is auto-generated from real traffic. New team members or frontend devs can import it into Postman, Insomnia, or wherever, and have full API documentation with real examples — without anyone having to write a single line of documentation manually."

---

## ✅ CLOSING — Value Summary (1 min)

**Say:**
> "So to summarize what this platform gives a team:
>
> 1. **Zero setup mocking** — point it at your backend, let it learn.
> 2. **Realistic AI responses** — not hardcoded stubs, but contextually generated data.
> 3. **Drift detection** — you always know when the real API has changed.
> 4. **Health monitoring** — you always know if performance is degrading.
> 5. **Auto-generated documentation** — OpenAPI spec from real traffic.
>
> The idea is that the mock should be as close to the real thing as possible — and it should stay close automatically, without any manual work."

---

## ❓ Anticipated Manager Questions

| Question | Answer |
|---|---|
| **"What if the real API isn't available at all to start with?"** | The platform needs at least a few real requests to learn from. Without that, it operates on a generic fallback. In that case, a developer can manually define an endpoint schema from the dashboard. |
| **"How do you handle authentication on the proxied requests?"** | All auth headers are passed through transparently. The platform doesn't strip or modify headers on the way to the real backend. |
| **"What's the database setup?"** | SQLite for local dev — zero setup, just run the server. PostgreSQL for production, hosted on Render. The codebase handles both automatically based on environment variables. |
| **"Does this work with REST only, or GraphQL too?"** | Currently REST/HTTP only. GraphQL has a different request structure that would need specific support. |
| **"What's the cost of the AI generation?"** | It uses `gpt-4o-mini` with a max of 2000 tokens per response. That's roughly $0.002–$0.004 per mock response. In practice, this is only called when a client hits the endpoint in mock mode — it's not called during learning. |
| **"Is this production-ready?"** | The core engine is solid. The main gap is test coverage — I'd want to add integration tests for the learning loop and drift detector before considering it production-grade. |
| **"Where's the source code?"** | Available on the project repo. The architecture is documented in the server entry point with clear module separation — `core/`, `routers/`, `services/`, `utils/`. |

---

> [!TIP]
> **Pre-demo checklist:**
> - [ ] Server is running locally (`uvicorn src.mock_server:app --reload`)
> - [ ] At least 5–10 real requests have been proxied so the learning engine has data
> - [ ] At least one endpoint has a drift alert (or be ready to simulate one)
> - [ ] `OPENAI_API_KEY` is set in [.env](file:///d:/Edutainer/intelligent-adaptive-mock/.env) for the AI demo
> - [ ] Browser is logged in via Firebase so the dashboard is accessible
> - [ ] Have a `curl` command ready in a terminal tab for the mock mode demo

> [!NOTE]
> Keep the tone conversational — you built this, you understand it deeply. Don't read off slides. Let the UI do the talking and narrate what's happening and *why* it matters.
